    <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-3 gap-8">
      <div class="lg:col-span-2">

    <Breadcrumb items={breadcrumbs} />

    <h1>Kanha Barasingha 2026 — The Swamp Deer Conservation Success Story</h1>

        <TrustBar category="Travel Guide" readingTime={8} />

        <p class="text-lg italic text-gray-600 mb-6">Last updated: July 18, 2026</p>

    <Hero
      src="/images/Untitled-design-3.webp"
      alt="Hard-ground Barasingha (swamp deer) in Kanha National Park meadows"
      caption="Kanha's Barasingha population recovered from 66 animals in 1970 to 800+ today"
    />

    <section class="answer-block">
      <p>
        Kanha's Barasingha (Rucervus duvaucelii branderi), also called the swamp deer, is a unique hard-ground
        subspecies found <strong>only at Kanha National Park</strong>. By 1970, the population had crashed to
        just <strong>66 animals</strong> due to habitat loss and disease, threatening extinction. Through
        dedicated conservation efforts including habitat management, veterinary care, and breeding programs,
        the population has recovered to approximately <strong>800-850 individuals</strong> today. Herds are
        commonly spotted grazing in Kanha Zone meadows, particularly around Sonph, Maasahi, Hallon, and Banjar.
        This recovery represents one of the world's most successful ungulate conservation stories and remains
        a flagship achievement for Kanha alongside tiger conservation.
      </p>
    </section>

    <Backlink       title="Plan Your Kanha Jungle Safari Package"
      description="Looking for complete Kanha jungle safari packages with accommodation, meals, and forest permits? Wildmark Resort near Khatia Gate offers all-inclusive Kanha safari booking."
      anchorText="Book Kanha Jungle Safari Package"
      ctaText="Kanha Safari Booking Online"
      primaryUrl="https://kanhasafaristay.com/blog/wildlife-of-kanha-national-park-beyond-the-tiger/"
      primaryAnchor="Kanha Barasingha Wildlife Guide"
      secondaryUrl="https://kanhasafaristay.com/blog/best-time-to-visit-kanha-national-park-for-tiger-safari/"
      secondaryAnchor="Best Time for Kanha Barasingha"
      tertiaryUrl="https://kanhasafaristay.com/faq/"
      tertiaryAnchor="Kanha Wildlife FAQ"
    />

    <h2>What is Barasingha?</h2>

    <p>
      Barasingha (Rucervus duvaucelii) means "twelve-horned" in Hindi, referring to the typical antler count of
      males (which can have 10-14 tines). The species is divided into three subspecies:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Hard-ground Barasingha (R. d. branderi):</strong> Found ONLY at Kanha; adapted for hard ground</li>
      <li><strong>Soft-ground Barasingha (R. d. duvaucelii):</strong> Found in Uttar Pradesh, Madhya Pradesh, Assam</li>
      <li><strong>Eastern Swamp Deer (R. d. ranjitsinhi):</strong> Found only in Manas (Assam), critically endangered</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      Kanha's hard-ground subspecies is distinguished by its unique hard hooves adapted for the park's hard,
      dry meadows rather than the swampy habitats that soft-ground Barasingha prefer. This adaptation made the
      Kanha population particularly vulnerable when meadows began degrading.
    </p>

    <h2>The Barasingha Conservation Story</h2>

    <p>
      The Barasingha conservation story at Kanha is one of the most remarkable species recovery efforts in
      conservation history.
    </p>

    <h3>Pre-1970 Crisis</h3>
    <p>
      Before focused conservation efforts, Kanha's Barasingha population declined precipitously. Habitat
      degradation from grazing, fire, and vegetation succession reduced the open meadows that Barasingha
      depend on. By 1970, only <strong>66 animals</strong> remained — a critical low that threatened the
      entire subspecies with extinction.
    </p>

    <h3>Conservation Interventions (1970-Present)</h3>
    <p>
      Kanha's forest department and conservation partners implemented a multi-pronged recovery strategy:
    </p>

    <ol>
      <li><strong>Meadow management:</strong> Controlled burning, grass cutting, and grazing management to maintain open meadow habitats</li>
      <li><strong>Veterinary care:</strong> Treatment of diseased animals, parasite control, and captive breeding for injured individuals</li>
      <li><strong>Habitat expansion:</strong> Restoration of degraded meadows to create new grazing areas</li>
      <li><strong>Predator-prey balance:</strong> Management of tiger and leopard predation pressure</li>
      <li><strong>Research and monitoring:</strong> Scientific tracking, population censuses, and genetic studies</li>
    </ol>

    <h3>Population Recovery Timeline</h3>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Year</th><th>Population</th><th>Key Event</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>1970</td><td>66</td><td>Crisis low; conservation intervention begins</td></tr>
        <tr><td>1980</td><td>120</td><td>First major recovery milestone</td></tr>
        <tr><td>1990</td><td>300+</td><td>Population crosses crisis threshold</td></tr>
        <tr><td>2000</td><td>500+</td><td>Subspecies considered safe</td></tr>
        <tr><td>2010</td><td>700+</td><td>Stable, growing population</td></tr>
        <tr><td>2024</td><td>800-850</td><td>Conservation success established</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <Backlink       title="See Barasingha on Kanha Safari"
      description="Wildmark Resort near Khatia Gate offers morning safaris to Kanha Zone meadows where Barasingha herds are commonly spotted. Multi-day packages available."
      primaryUrl="https://kanhasafaristay.com/blog/wildlife-of-kanha-national-park-beyond-the-tiger/"
      primaryAnchor="Kanha Barasingha Wildlife Guide"
