    <h2>Where to See Barasingha at Kanha</h2>

    <p>
      Barasingha are most easily spotted in <strong>Kanha Zone meadows</strong>, accessed via the main Khatia
      Gate. The park's iconic meadows attract herds of Barasingha that graze in open grasslands, particularly
      during morning and late afternoon hours.
    </p>

    <h3>Top Barasingha Viewing Locations</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Sonph Meadow:</strong> Reliable Barasingha sightings, especially during summer</li>
      <li><strong>Maasahi Meadow:</strong> Smaller herds, excellent photography</li>
      <li><strong>Hallon Meadow:</strong> Large herds, scenic landscapes</li>
      <li><strong>Banjar Meadow:</strong> Mixed herds with chital and sambar</li>
      <li><strong>Kisli Zone Edges:</strong> Forest-meadow transition areas</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Barasingha Behavior and Biology</h2>

    <h3>Physical Characteristics</h3>
    <p>
      Adult male Barasingha stand 130-140 cm at the shoulder and weigh 170-200 kg. Their most distinctive
      feature is the multi-tined antlers (typically 10-14 tines, sometimes up to 20). Females are smaller,
      weighing 120-150 kg, and generally antlerless.
    </p>

    <h3>Social Behavior</h3>
    <p>
      Barasingha live in herds typically ranging from 5-30 animals. Herds are matriarchal, with dominant females
      leading grazing patterns. Males join herds during rutting season (October-November) and form bachelor
      groups outside breeding periods.
    </p>

    <h3>Diet and Grazing</h3>
    <p>
      Barasingha are grazers, primarily feeding on grasses, herbs, and aquatic plants. Their preference for
      short, fresh grass makes them dependent on well-managed meadows. They typically graze during morning
      and late afternoon, resting in shaded forest edges during midday heat.
    </p>

    <h3>Reproduction</h3>
    <p>
      Barasingha breed from October to February, with peak activity in November-December. After a gestation
      period of approximately 240-270 days, females give birth to one or two fawns between June and August.
      Fawns remain hidden in vegetation for the first few weeks before joining the herd.
    </p>

    <h2>Conservation Status</h2>

    <p>
      The hard-ground Barasingha is classified as <strong>Vulnerable</strong> by the IUCN, with the entire
      global population existing within Kanha National Park. While the population has recovered significantly,
      the subspecies remains entirely dependent on Kanha's continued habitat management. Any major habitat
      disruption — disease outbreak, catastrophic fire, or significant predator imbalance — could threaten
      the population again.
    </p>

    <h2>Best Time to See Barasingha</h2>

    <p>
      Barasingha are visible year-round at Kanha, but certain seasons offer better viewing opportunities:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Winter (November-February):</strong> Cool weather, herds active in meadows during morning and late afternoon</li>
      <li><strong>Summer (March-May):</strong> Concentrated near water sources, easy to spot</li>
      <li><strong>Rutting Season (October-November):</strong> Males display territorial behavior, antlers fully developed</li>
      <li><strong>Monsoon (July-September):</strong> Park closed for safaris</li>
    </ul>

